00:04:43.640 --> 00:04:46.720
So to start things off, I think it's

00:04:46.720 --> 00:04:52.559
quite critical to provide a definition of data product

00:04:52.559 --> 00:04:54.359
and data as a product.

00:04:54.359 --> 00:04:56.720
If you have heard of this term, you

00:04:56.720 --> 00:05:00.000
might have noticed that in different circles,

00:05:00.000 --> 00:05:05.279
in different groups, it could mean quite different concepts.

00:05:05.279 --> 00:05:08.920
How we are defining data product

00:05:08.920 --> 00:05:15.359
is simply a data object that, much like any other products,

00:05:15.359 --> 00:05:19.640
come with a set of characteristics or attributes.

00:05:19.640 --> 00:05:27.079
So specifically, we call data product,

00:05:27.079 --> 00:05:29.320
this notion of data product, to be a data object that

00:05:29.320 --> 00:05:31.160
is use case driven.

00:05:31.160 --> 00:05:34.160
This is in contrast with, quote unquote,

00:05:34.160 --> 00:05:36.679
wrangled data that can serve any purpose.

00:05:36.679 --> 00:05:39.079
It's clean data, and you can use it for whatever purpose.

00:05:39.079 --> 00:05:41.119
So this has to be, the data product

00:05:41.119 --> 00:05:46.040
has to have a specific user story or a set of coherent

00:05:46.040 --> 00:05:48.239
objectives that it achieves.

00:05:48.239 --> 00:05:51.760
Now, if you have that level of specificity,

00:05:51.760 --> 00:05:54.880
you can imagine that you may have slightly different use

00:05:54.880 --> 00:06:00.079
cases leading to a variety of different data objects.

00:06:00.079 --> 00:06:03.320
So it becomes even more critical to be able to version control

00:06:03.359 --> 00:06:04.079
it and track it.

00:06:04.079 --> 00:06:07.799
So as you have different, slightly different data sets,

00:06:07.799 --> 00:06:09.359
you should be able to branch it.

00:06:09.359 --> 00:06:11.559
You should be able to version track it.

00:06:11.559 --> 00:06:16.079
So making it use case specific and being able, then,

00:06:16.079 --> 00:06:21.119
to branch it and version track it becomes quite critical.

00:06:21.119 --> 00:06:22.920
It needs to be tested.

00:06:22.920 --> 00:06:25.279
It needs to be reproducible.

00:06:25.279 --> 00:06:28.640
And I would say not only reproducible, but easily

00:06:28.640 --> 00:06:31.359
reproducible, meaning that with a handful of commands,

00:06:31.359 --> 00:06:33.959
you can just reproduce the data.

00:06:33.959 --> 00:06:36.839
It should be easily maintainable, extensible.

00:06:36.839 --> 00:06:42.200
Think about this as your typical R package in this context.

00:06:42.200 --> 00:06:45.440
So in this context of R users, you

00:06:45.440 --> 00:06:47.880
can use an R package for whatever end

00:06:47.880 --> 00:06:50.320
that you have in your analysis or otherwise.

00:06:50.320 --> 00:06:52.200
You can also use that to integrate it

00:06:52.200 --> 00:06:55.959
into a new R package and build upon it and extend it.

00:06:55.959 --> 00:06:57.720
Same should apply to data products.

00:06:57.720 --> 00:07:00.600
You should be able to integrate it into a new data product,

00:07:01.519 --> 00:07:04.200
bring a few of them together, build upon them, extend them.

00:07:04.200 --> 00:07:06.320
So it should be extensible.

00:07:06.320 --> 00:07:09.480
It should be findable, accessible, and portable.

00:07:09.480 --> 00:07:14.640
And notes on that last one is that as data scientists,

00:07:14.640 --> 00:07:19.799
if I may speak for a lot of us, that we may not necessarily

00:07:19.799 --> 00:07:26.160
be super conscious or have concerns about whether my data

00:07:26.160 --> 00:07:30.839
is coming from Azure or AWS S3 or whatever platform,

00:07:30.839 --> 00:07:34.399
whatever infrastructure I have.

00:07:34.399 --> 00:07:38.480
But our colleagues in IT or other places, they may.

00:07:38.480 --> 00:07:41.359
So as my data, as the requirements

00:07:41.359 --> 00:07:43.279
of my organization changes, I need

00:07:43.279 --> 00:07:48.320
to take my data from, let's say, AWS S3 to Azure or vice versa

00:07:48.320 --> 00:07:50.519
or to some network drive.

00:07:50.519 --> 00:07:52.679
All of these characteristics that we talked about

00:07:52.679 --> 00:07:53.559
should go along.

00:07:53.559 --> 00:07:54.980
So it shouldn't be something that

00:07:55.220 --> 00:07:57.859
is dependent on the platform or technology

00:07:57.859 --> 00:08:00.019
outside of the data product.

00:08:00.019 --> 00:08:01.380
These core set of features, there

00:08:01.380 --> 00:08:05.420
could be other features that are dependent on the platform.

00:08:05.420 --> 00:08:10.380
So these core set of characteristics and attributes

00:08:10.380 --> 00:08:15.299
define what we call a data product.

00:08:15.299 --> 00:08:18.859
Now, data as a product is a framework

00:08:18.859 --> 00:08:21.700
to make it practical for data science teams

00:08:21.700 --> 00:08:24.579
to pull together their data wrangling efforts

00:08:24.660 --> 00:08:27.339
towards collaboratively building data products.

00:08:27.339 --> 00:08:32.780
So on one hand, we have this product.

00:08:32.780 --> 00:08:34.859
On the other hand, we have a set of processes

00:08:34.859 --> 00:08:40.020
that allows us to easily, or at least methodically,

00:08:40.020 --> 00:08:42.299
build these data products.

00:08:42.299 --> 00:08:46.260
So the processes could be agreements between the teams,

00:08:46.260 --> 00:08:52.739
like how we want to use the conventions of coding,

00:08:52.739 --> 00:08:56.099
as well as some automations and tools that allow us

00:08:56.099 --> 00:08:58.859
to implement those agreements.

00:08:58.859 --> 00:09:02.179
So data as a product, you can think about as a framework,

00:09:02.179 --> 00:09:05.340
way of thinking, as well as the tool sets

00:09:05.340 --> 00:09:08.059
that allow us to implement that way of thinking.

00:09:08.059 --> 00:09:10.820
Data product is the output.

00:09:10.820 --> 00:09:15.059
So with that out of the way, as far as the definition goes,

00:09:15.059 --> 00:09:17.979
looking at these attributes, perhaps it's

00:09:17.979 --> 00:09:20.940
not difficult to imagine a variety of motivations

00:09:20.940 --> 00:09:25.460
why a data science team may be interested in adopting

00:09:25.460 --> 00:09:29.419
a framework that will lead to their data sets or data

00:09:29.419 --> 00:09:32.820
objects coming out with all of these attributes.

00:09:32.820 --> 00:09:34.500
But to focus on one, perhaps you can

00:09:34.500 --> 00:09:37.859
think about this 80-20 rule of data science, which

00:09:37.859 --> 00:09:41.460
is basically this observation made by a lot of the data

00:09:41.460 --> 00:09:47.739
scientists that a typical week could involve four days out

00:09:47.739 --> 00:09:53.900
of that five working days that you are engaged in data

00:09:53.900 --> 00:09:58.820
processing or data wrangling, whatever you call it.

00:09:58.820 --> 00:10:01.619
And then on that last day, you may get a chance

00:10:01.619 --> 00:10:02.979
to actually do your data analysis.

00:10:02.979 --> 00:10:11.020
So as a data scientist or leader of a data science team,

00:10:11.020 --> 00:10:13.820
if you are interested in adding more agility

00:10:13.820 --> 00:10:22.299
to your overall team efforts, it

00:10:22.299 --> 00:10:25.820
is fair to look at this data processing

00:10:25.820 --> 00:10:29.260
and try to bring in additional agility to it

00:10:29.260 --> 00:10:31.020
and efficiency to it.

00:10:31.020 --> 00:10:36.780
And there are a variety of approaches

00:10:36.780 --> 00:10:38.700
that teams have implemented.

00:10:38.700 --> 00:10:43.739
Hopefully, we all work in teams that heroic data wrangling

00:10:43.739 --> 00:10:45.179
is not one of those approaches.

00:10:45.179 --> 00:10:51.219
No one is advocating for shrinking that 80% to 30%

00:10:51.219 --> 00:10:55.500
by just willpower and working extra hours.

00:10:55.500 --> 00:10:57.780
Hopefully, that is not the case.

00:10:57.780 --> 00:10:59.859
But then there are things like new data agreements

00:10:59.859 --> 00:11:01.900
that you may put in place with data vendors.

00:11:01.900 --> 00:11:04.260
You may ask your data platform to do more

00:11:04.260 --> 00:11:06.460
in the way of data validation.

00:11:06.460 --> 00:11:09.380
Even pushing that validation of data

00:11:09.380 --> 00:11:13.419
further upstream into your pipelines, that could help.

00:11:13.460 --> 00:11:17.780
In some cases, it may seem appealing or maybe appealing

00:11:17.780 --> 00:11:21.179
to extend the capacity of your data science team

00:11:21.179 --> 00:11:24.500
if the resource is limited within the data science team

00:11:24.500 --> 00:11:26.739
to extend the capacity of the data science team

00:11:26.739 --> 00:11:29.340
by bringing additional resources that could then

00:11:29.340 --> 00:11:33.539
help with just the task of building data.

00:11:33.539 --> 00:11:37.539
However, one caveat around that is, particularly

00:11:37.539 --> 00:11:40.780
in the case of pharma, you can think

00:11:40.780 --> 00:11:46.419
about how much domain knowledge and expertise is needed

00:11:46.419 --> 00:11:49.260
and gets factored in as we are processing the data.

00:11:49.260 --> 00:11:52.260
So science and context can be missed.

00:11:52.260 --> 00:11:54.179
And so that is a caveat.

00:11:54.179 --> 00:11:57.140
But setting that aside, these ideas

00:11:57.140 --> 00:12:00.500
as similar approaches collectively

00:12:00.500 --> 00:12:04.900
perhaps provide some level of relief.

00:12:04.900 --> 00:12:07.299
Perhaps a slightly different view

00:12:07.299 --> 00:12:11.140
would be rather than seeking relief,

00:12:11.140 --> 00:12:14.539
we can acknowledge that here's my team spending

00:12:14.539 --> 00:12:18.099
their precious time and resources and expertise.

00:12:18.099 --> 00:12:21.619
I should emphasize that expertise part.

00:12:21.619 --> 00:12:25.539
Building something, so there's a lot of value in that.

00:12:25.539 --> 00:12:32.580
If 80% of my team is building this artifact or output,

00:12:32.580 --> 00:12:34.619
that has a lot of value in it.

00:12:34.619 --> 00:12:39.659
So instead of thinking about or along the way

00:12:39.659 --> 00:12:43.739
of thinking about reducing that time to getting that,

00:12:43.739 --> 00:12:48.340
can I also think about how can I drive more value

00:12:48.340 --> 00:12:50.340
from this precious resource?

00:12:50.340 --> 00:12:53.659
And if I'm thinking in that sense,

00:12:53.659 --> 00:12:59.340
I'm not trying to remove the burden of this effort.

00:12:59.340 --> 00:13:01.460
I'm just trying to drive more value from it.

00:13:01.460 --> 00:13:05.340
But to alleviate that burden, help with that,

00:13:05.340 --> 00:13:06.940
I can also make collaboration easy.

00:13:06.940 --> 00:13:10.940
So that big lift is shared across the team.

00:13:10.940 --> 00:13:12.659
So it becomes a little bit easier.

00:13:12.659 --> 00:13:14.539
So you make collaboration easy.

00:13:14.539 --> 00:13:20.260
When permissible, you can add a dash of automated standards

00:13:20.260 --> 00:13:26.539
and make, put in place processes, process frameworks

00:13:26.539 --> 00:13:27.419
for collaboration.

00:13:27.419 --> 00:13:29.820
So not surprisingly, perhaps at this point,

00:13:30.340 --> 00:13:33.380
you can imagine that this latter approach of driving more value

00:13:33.380 --> 00:13:38.340
from data wrangling is what the framework of data

00:13:38.340 --> 00:13:41.059
as a product, as we are defining it, advocates.

00:13:41.059 --> 00:13:44.580
So the idea is that you're bringing in your usual input

00:13:44.580 --> 00:13:48.260
data, and you're adding your logic of data wrangling.

00:13:48.260 --> 00:13:49.900
And then you feed it into this process

00:13:49.900 --> 00:13:52.739
that out would come a data product, which

00:13:52.739 --> 00:13:58.179
then can be fed into a number of utilities, analysis, apps,

00:13:58.179 --> 00:13:59.099
automated reports.

00:13:59.140 --> 00:14:01.820
And this data product now is reusable and extensible.

00:14:01.820 --> 00:14:06.340
So that work is essentially something that lives on.

00:14:06.340 --> 00:14:11.580
That in contrast with a typical workflow of a data scientist,

00:14:11.580 --> 00:14:14.099
which may include data wrangling,

00:14:14.099 --> 00:14:19.020
be so inseparably intertangled with your utility,

00:14:19.020 --> 00:14:22.700
be it analysis or otherwise, that once that analysis is done

00:14:22.700 --> 00:14:25.460
or once that utility has run its course,

00:14:25.460 --> 00:14:28.700
then that piece of data work is essentially

00:14:28.700 --> 00:14:29.340
disposable.

00:14:29.340 --> 00:14:33.380
So you have an expensive, very, very expensive effort

00:14:33.380 --> 00:14:37.020
that now has no more use.

00:14:37.020 --> 00:14:38.859
So up to this point, we have talked

00:14:38.859 --> 00:14:41.940
about this notion of data product in abstract.

00:14:41.940 --> 00:14:45.059
So let's think about what's our north star.

00:14:45.059 --> 00:14:46.580
What are we aiming for here?

00:14:46.580 --> 00:14:49.299
So as I alluded to earlier, it has

00:14:49.299 --> 00:14:51.260
to serve a coherent set of objectives.

00:14:51.260 --> 00:14:53.340
So this is one of the core requirements.

00:14:53.340 --> 00:14:55.539
Again, thinking about any product out there.

00:14:55.539 --> 00:14:58.700
If you have a vacuum cleaner, it's

00:14:58.700 --> 00:15:02.059
not going to be a hairdryer or an iron.

00:15:02.059 --> 00:15:06.380
So it has to have a coherent set of objectives.

00:15:06.380 --> 00:15:12.099
So that limits the scope of the effort.

00:15:12.099 --> 00:15:13.820
Even with a limited scope, you don't

00:15:13.820 --> 00:15:17.020
want to be building it from A to Z all in one shot.

00:15:17.020 --> 00:15:19.700
So think about, again, a product.

00:15:19.700 --> 00:15:21.419
Like you may have different components

00:15:21.419 --> 00:15:22.739
that you build and you assemble.

00:15:22.739 --> 00:15:26.099
It has to be built modularly.

00:15:26.099 --> 00:15:27.659
And if you are building it modularly

00:15:27.659 --> 00:15:29.820
and your buddy here is building some parts

00:15:29.820 --> 00:15:31.380
and you are building some parts of it

00:15:31.380 --> 00:15:33.460
and you're bringing it all together,

00:15:33.460 --> 00:15:38.940
it should be something that, while not totally

00:15:38.940 --> 00:15:41.179
setting the stone that you're doing exactly this way,

00:15:41.179 --> 00:15:44.059
it has to have, it shouldn't be something that is an art

00:15:44.059 --> 00:15:45.619
and everybody does it their own way.

00:15:45.619 --> 00:15:48.380
So collaboration requires some blueprint

00:15:48.380 --> 00:15:52.380
of how we are building these elements.

00:15:52.380 --> 00:15:55.299
Now, again, collaboration requires everything

00:15:55.299 --> 00:15:57.739
to be versioned so we don't get tangled up

00:15:57.739 --> 00:16:01.140
in what version of what elements we are

00:16:01.140 --> 00:16:03.059
talking about across the team.

00:16:03.059 --> 00:16:06.299
So by everything here, I mean code, environment, and data

00:16:06.299 --> 00:16:07.460
needs to be versioned.

00:16:07.460 --> 00:16:10.059
So all of the things that I've talked about so far,

00:16:10.059 --> 00:16:11.739
as far as the requirements of the product,

00:16:11.739 --> 00:16:13.820
has to do with the build process.

00:16:13.820 --> 00:16:16.859
But from a user perspective, it also has to be easy to use.

00:16:16.859 --> 00:16:19.059
So connect, list, get is all you need

00:16:19.059 --> 00:16:22.700
to be able to pull the data down and use it.

00:16:22.700 --> 00:16:24.659
So as a user, you should have an easy interface.

00:16:24.659 --> 00:16:26.780
And lastly, as I mentioned, we want

00:16:26.780 --> 00:16:29.179
to have it be platform agnostic.

00:16:29.179 --> 00:16:31.739
So if you're going from S3, later on you

00:16:31.739 --> 00:16:34.460
need to go to file systems and RStudio Connect

00:16:34.460 --> 00:16:36.460
is your next destination.

00:16:36.460 --> 00:16:40.380
The data science workflow should dictate where your data is

00:16:40.380 --> 00:16:43.299
or if there are other requirements that

00:16:43.299 --> 00:16:44.659
can be accommodated and you don't

00:16:44.659 --> 00:16:46.780
have to worry about the functionality of your data

00:16:47.340 --> 00:16:49.299
being compromised.

00:16:49.299 --> 00:16:52.059
Now, this is the product's requirement.

00:16:52.059 --> 00:16:54.179
And there should be a build tool that

00:16:54.179 --> 00:16:58.179
can enable building that product according to those attributes.

00:16:58.179 --> 00:17:04.739
So you can see the linkage here that a build tool,

00:17:04.739 --> 00:17:07.260
given all those attributes that I mentioned are requirements,

00:17:07.260 --> 00:17:09.660
should naturally support modular development,

00:17:09.660 --> 00:17:13.459
should minimize boilerplate, should enable reproducibility

00:17:13.500 --> 00:17:17.660
by capturing everything in the state of the code, data,

00:17:17.660 --> 00:17:21.619
and environment, should encourage best code style

00:17:21.619 --> 00:17:25.420
practices, should enable full traceability of everything,

00:17:25.420 --> 00:17:26.739
code, data, environment.

00:17:26.739 --> 00:17:30.020
And as a builder, you should not be learning a new language.

00:17:30.020 --> 00:17:32.619
If you know R, if you know Git, you should be good to go.

00:17:32.619 --> 00:17:36.099
Now, if this was instead of a data as a product,

00:17:36.099 --> 00:17:39.339
this was software as a product, you

00:17:39.380 --> 00:17:45.180
would rightly expect that the tool is already around.

00:17:45.180 --> 00:17:51.420
And in the rich set of tools and experiences and processes

00:17:51.420 --> 00:17:54.660
that have been developed and implemented

00:17:54.660 --> 00:17:58.459
by DevOps community, when we are talking about the software,

00:17:58.459 --> 00:18:03.660
we can accommodate all of those features of a build tool.

00:18:03.660 --> 00:18:07.260
The difference here is that not only we have code,

00:18:07.260 --> 00:18:08.260
but we have data.

00:18:08.260 --> 00:18:10.739
So this gives us an inspiration that if we

00:18:10.739 --> 00:18:13.020
were able to capture data as code,

00:18:13.020 --> 00:18:19.260
we would then build a bridge to this rich set of tools

00:18:19.260 --> 00:18:23.540
and experiences that are available in the DevOps

00:18:23.540 --> 00:18:28.540
community and put those to use for our end.

00:18:28.540 --> 00:18:34.979
So building with data as a code, what's the approach here?

00:18:34.979 --> 00:18:36.859
So thinking about the concept there.

00:18:37.380 --> 00:18:40.739
Let me walk through an example of how

00:18:40.739 --> 00:18:42.619
this could work conceptually.

00:18:42.619 --> 00:18:46.459
So let's say you are here in this point one.

00:18:46.459 --> 00:18:47.500
You have some data sets.

00:18:47.500 --> 00:18:48.939
Some of you in pharma are familiar

00:18:48.939 --> 00:18:49.939
with this nomenclature.

00:18:49.939 --> 00:18:51.939
So let's say you have some LV data, which

00:18:51.939 --> 00:18:54.979
is this lab data collected on a cohort of patients.

00:18:54.979 --> 00:18:59.500
You have some medication data and a bunch more data sets

00:18:59.500 --> 00:19:01.819
that you have at your disposal.

00:19:01.819 --> 00:19:03.660
Now, you start your project.

00:19:03.660 --> 00:19:06.579
You set the initialization in motion.

00:19:07.500 --> 00:19:10.020
It starts capturing the environments

00:19:10.020 --> 00:19:11.420
that you're developing in.

00:19:11.420 --> 00:19:16.780
It adds the remote locations for your code, for your data.

00:19:16.780 --> 00:19:18.219
So that initialization is done.

00:19:18.219 --> 00:19:22.420
Now, you go ahead and onboard your data into your data

00:19:22.420 --> 00:19:22.939
product.

00:19:22.939 --> 00:19:25.060
So let's start with this LV, which

00:19:25.060 --> 00:19:27.260
is this collection of lab measurements

00:19:27.260 --> 00:19:29.619
on a cohort of patients you have.

00:19:29.619 --> 00:19:31.459
And so you bring that in.

00:19:31.459 --> 00:19:34.180
And let's say you can now sync that

00:19:34.180 --> 00:19:36.060
to your remote location, which you have already

00:19:36.060 --> 00:19:38.300
defined at the initialization.

00:19:38.300 --> 00:19:40.020
So at this stage, this is the part

00:19:40.020 --> 00:19:47.099
that perhaps worth attention is that you can capture this data

00:19:47.099 --> 00:19:48.859
that you're pushing to a remote location

00:19:48.859 --> 00:19:52.459
with a set of metadata in a way that uniquely identifies that.

00:19:52.459 --> 00:19:55.420
So you're capturing some metadata,

00:19:55.420 --> 00:19:58.579
like the label for that data, like some description.

00:19:58.579 --> 00:20:01.380
And this version, which could be essentially

00:20:01.380 --> 00:20:05.699
a SHA hash of that data, or any other flavor of getting

00:20:05.699 --> 00:20:07.219
some sort of a hash for that data,

00:20:07.219 --> 00:20:09.140
uniquely identifies that data set.

00:20:09.140 --> 00:20:12.219
And some additional set of metadata

00:20:12.219 --> 00:20:15.739
that then will help you retrieve this data when

00:20:15.739 --> 00:20:17.060
you have the need for it.

00:20:17.060 --> 00:20:20.020
So now you have converted your data

00:20:20.020 --> 00:20:21.859
to a set of metadata that uniquely

00:20:21.859 --> 00:20:24.739
identifies and gives some description about that data.

00:20:24.739 --> 00:20:27.420
And if you capture that, as you repeat

00:20:27.420 --> 00:20:29.500
adding additional data sets, you build

00:20:29.540 --> 00:20:31.260
a manifest that has all the information

00:20:31.260 --> 00:20:33.739
you need for your input data.

00:20:33.739 --> 00:20:36.739
And that is the approach of converting data to code.

00:20:36.739 --> 00:20:39.780
Then as you add additional layers of code for logic

00:20:39.780 --> 00:20:42.579
and you're capturing your environment, all of this

00:20:42.579 --> 00:20:43.420
is code.

00:20:43.420 --> 00:20:44.180
You can commit it.

00:20:44.180 --> 00:20:45.260
You can push it.

00:20:45.260 --> 00:20:48.819
And when you have done that pushing,

00:20:48.819 --> 00:20:50.900
in your remote GitHub repository,

00:20:50.900 --> 00:20:52.300
now you have the build logic, you

00:20:52.300 --> 00:20:53.780
have the package dependency, and you

00:20:53.780 --> 00:20:56.180
have all the information you need

00:20:56.180 --> 00:20:58.459
to identify the input data.

00:20:58.459 --> 00:21:02.180
Now, this recipe is complete in a way

00:21:02.180 --> 00:21:04.939
that a colleague sitting at this point four

00:21:04.939 --> 00:21:06.859
or maybe a CI CD machine that gets

00:21:06.859 --> 00:21:12.579
triggered by the push sitting downstream

00:21:12.579 --> 00:21:15.780
can build this from scratch and push it again

00:21:15.780 --> 00:21:20.099
to the same remote data repository in the same fashion,

00:21:20.099 --> 00:21:21.979
capturing the same set of metadata.

00:21:21.979 --> 00:21:25.060
Now, everything here has been converted into code.

00:21:25.060 --> 00:21:27.260
So your data lives in its data location.

00:21:27.260 --> 00:21:28.939
Your code lives in the code location.

00:21:28.939 --> 00:21:30.900
And as long as you have access to both,

00:21:30.900 --> 00:21:32.819
you can build it from scratch.

00:21:32.819 --> 00:21:38.500
We have implemented this framework in R.

00:21:38.500 --> 00:21:42.859
So it's a family of R packages we call gapper.

00:21:42.859 --> 00:21:49.859
And it is available for use to build, essentially,

00:21:49.859 --> 00:21:52.819
implement the framework that I just shared with you all.

00:21:52.859 --> 00:21:58.140
So this family of package consists of three packages,

00:21:58.140 --> 00:22:00.619
dpi, dpdeploy, dpbuild.

00:22:00.619 --> 00:22:03.140
Why three packages, you may ask.

00:22:03.140 --> 00:22:05.219
I can come up with a couple of different answers,

00:22:05.219 --> 00:22:08.699
historically, in terms of the bulk and code management.

00:22:08.699 --> 00:22:10.819
But perhaps the most important one

00:22:10.819 --> 00:22:14.939
is that you can think about three different persona that

00:22:14.939 --> 00:22:16.300
would be using these packages.

00:22:16.300 --> 00:22:18.459
So starting with dpi, it means it's

00:22:18.459 --> 00:22:21.660
meant to simplify access to data products.

00:22:21.660 --> 00:22:24.500
So if you are just a user, whether it's

00:22:24.500 --> 00:22:26.859
an application or a report, you only

00:22:26.859 --> 00:22:29.819
need a handful of functions to be able to access the data

00:22:29.819 --> 00:22:30.300
products.

00:22:30.300 --> 00:22:34.619
So you don't need the bulk of the rest of the packages.

00:22:34.619 --> 00:22:38.579
dpbuild is meant to simplify building of data products.

00:22:38.579 --> 00:22:40.260
This is the bulkiest of the packages.

00:22:40.260 --> 00:22:42.540
This is used by the data developer.

00:22:42.540 --> 00:22:44.099
So you can think about the persona here

00:22:44.099 --> 00:22:45.060
as the data developer.

00:22:45.060 --> 00:22:49.699
dpdeploy can be a data developer.

00:22:49.699 --> 00:22:53.219
Or it can be a workflow automation machine.

00:22:53.219 --> 00:22:56.540
So you have the task of dpdeploys

00:22:56.540 --> 00:22:58.939
to simplify sync and deployment of data products.

00:22:58.939 --> 00:23:02.819
So you can have a CI-CD process set up

00:23:02.819 --> 00:23:05.140
where, as your data comes in, it gets pushed.

00:23:05.140 --> 00:23:07.459
It's kind of like a shuttling of the data

00:23:07.459 --> 00:23:12.380
from a location that is some workstation

00:23:12.380 --> 00:23:15.780
to the remote location.

00:23:15.780 --> 00:23:17.260
But how does this?

00:23:17.260 --> 00:23:19.140
So now that we have thought about all of this,

00:23:19.260 --> 00:23:21.260
how does this all come together?

00:23:21.260 --> 00:23:25.300
So there are a variety of workflows

00:23:25.300 --> 00:23:28.660
that a dapper needs to accommodate.

00:23:28.660 --> 00:23:30.739
Like when you write code, you don't always

00:23:30.739 --> 00:23:32.900
start from setting up your project

00:23:32.900 --> 00:23:35.140
and going all the way to deployment.

00:23:35.140 --> 00:23:37.819
So you may set up your project, develop some,

00:23:37.819 --> 00:23:42.739
go do something else, come back, have some pull requests coming

00:23:42.739 --> 00:23:45.660
your way, change that, deploy.

00:23:45.660 --> 00:23:49.020
So there's a lot of different workflows

00:23:49.020 --> 00:23:50.780
that needs to be accommodated.

00:23:50.780 --> 00:23:54.939
But perhaps to just kind of provide an end-to-end example,

00:23:54.939 --> 00:23:57.819
if you were to start from the beginning and go to the end,

00:23:57.819 --> 00:23:59.219
it would look something like this.

00:23:59.219 --> 00:24:03.780
So you start with that DP in it, which sets up your project.

00:24:03.780 --> 00:24:05.540
It's kind of like when you do Git in it.

00:24:05.540 --> 00:24:07.939
So it sets up your project.

00:24:07.939 --> 00:24:10.979
You add your data, so you onboard your data.

00:24:10.979 --> 00:24:12.979
We are, again, encouraging best practices.

00:24:12.979 --> 00:24:15.380
We are encouraging folks to spend a little bit of time

00:24:15.380 --> 00:24:17.219
here making sure the data they're onboarding

00:24:17.219 --> 00:24:19.900
is actually what they want to onboard.

00:24:19.900 --> 00:24:22.339
Then you add your logic of the code,

00:24:22.339 --> 00:24:25.020
and then you deploy the code and data.

00:24:25.020 --> 00:24:28.380
So at this point, essentially, everything

00:24:28.380 --> 00:24:30.619
has been put out there, data and codes,

00:24:30.619 --> 00:24:34.859
for anyone who has access and granted access

00:24:34.859 --> 00:24:37.780
to be able to access the code and access the data.

00:24:37.780 --> 00:24:41.099
Now, what I want to emphasize here

00:24:41.099 --> 00:24:46.739
is that this step is adding your code

00:24:46.739 --> 00:24:51.180
is the step that should take the bulk of your time.

00:24:51.180 --> 00:24:53.619
Whether or not you're using Dapr,

00:24:53.619 --> 00:24:55.900
you need to spend some time developing

00:24:55.900 --> 00:24:57.859
that logic of data processing.

00:24:57.859 --> 00:25:00.219
So the idea here is that if you, let's say,

00:25:00.219 --> 00:25:03.380
today spend an hour on a particular project

00:25:03.380 --> 00:25:05.459
or two hours on a particular project

00:25:05.459 --> 00:25:08.979
just doing the data processing part,

00:25:08.979 --> 00:25:13.020
now bringing that into the Dapr framework,

00:25:13.020 --> 00:25:16.619
you're adding maybe 5, 10 more minutes on top of that.

00:25:16.619 --> 00:25:18.819
But still, the bulk of your effort remains the same.

00:25:18.819 --> 00:25:21.459
So the boilerplate should be minimized.

00:25:21.459 --> 00:25:23.099
Now, this is the claim.

00:25:23.099 --> 00:25:27.819
And we're going to go through an example, a toy example,

00:25:27.819 --> 00:25:29.140
that hopefully shows this.

00:25:29.140 --> 00:25:33.660
The toy example is overly simplistic, admittedly.

00:25:33.660 --> 00:25:36.420
We are starting from the cars data set.

00:25:36.420 --> 00:25:42.660
And if I recall correctly, this data set

00:25:42.660 --> 00:25:44.380
comes with a number of cars.

00:25:44.380 --> 00:25:49.020
And I believe there is a column that

00:25:49.020 --> 00:25:52.140
is about the distance from the point

00:25:52.140 --> 00:25:56.540
that a car or driver applies the brake and the car starts.

00:25:56.540 --> 00:25:59.140
I think that's the case.

00:25:59.140 --> 00:26:01.660
So that column is in British units.

00:26:01.660 --> 00:26:04.260
And let's say the user story that you have

00:26:04.260 --> 00:26:07.300
asks you to convert that to a metric unit.

00:26:07.300 --> 00:26:09.579
Overly simplistic vignette.

00:26:09.579 --> 00:26:11.060
And actually, this vignette is also

00:26:11.060 --> 00:26:13.859
in the vignette for the package, so if you wanted to check it

00:26:13.859 --> 00:26:16.540
out more closely.

00:26:16.540 --> 00:26:20.859
But being overly simplistic, still, the wiring and setup

00:26:20.859 --> 00:26:24.060
of the project is identical to a bigger project that

00:26:24.060 --> 00:26:26.859
may be more realistic with tons of data and tons of logic.

00:26:26.859 --> 00:26:28.420
So going through that, hopefully,

00:26:28.420 --> 00:26:32.420
give us a sense of what's the degree of boilerplate

00:26:32.420 --> 00:26:35.300
and the time that we need to allow for that.

00:26:35.300 --> 00:26:38.300
So we start with this setup step.

00:26:38.300 --> 00:26:40.500
Again, thinking about all the steps that I mentioned

00:26:40.500 --> 00:26:42.780
in the previous setup data code deploy.

00:26:42.780 --> 00:26:44.219
So we're going to go through that.

00:26:44.219 --> 00:26:47.300
So setup here, simply, there's this function,

00:26:47.300 --> 00:26:50.540
vpinit, that sets up your project folder,

00:26:50.540 --> 00:26:54.819
runs git init, captures your environment thanks to RN.

00:26:54.819 --> 00:26:59.380
So it does the RN init, adds remote for code and data,

00:26:59.380 --> 00:27:01.260
and records project metadata.

00:27:01.459 --> 00:27:05.699
Let's take a look at how this looks in practice.

00:27:05.699 --> 00:27:07.420
So this video, we are essentially

00:27:07.420 --> 00:27:09.060
going through that initialization step.

00:27:09.060 --> 00:27:11.459
So we are bringing in the library.

00:27:11.459 --> 00:27:15.859
We are setting up some promises for credential

00:27:15.859 --> 00:27:18.660
that we need to access.

00:27:18.660 --> 00:27:21.540
We are not providing a credential to the framework.

00:27:21.540 --> 00:27:23.819
We're just saying, these are the environment variables

00:27:23.819 --> 00:27:27.260
you will need when you are ready to build the data product.

00:27:27.300 --> 00:27:31.420
And we are putting that into this vpinit.

00:27:31.420 --> 00:27:33.500
We are also providing the location

00:27:33.500 --> 00:27:36.500
of where the data needs to go.

00:27:36.500 --> 00:27:38.420
And then we execute this vpinit,

00:27:38.420 --> 00:27:42.020
so which takes in as parameters some metadata.

00:27:42.020 --> 00:27:42.939
What's the branch name?

00:27:42.939 --> 00:27:43.900
What's the project name?

00:27:43.900 --> 00:27:44.859
What's the user's story?

00:27:44.859 --> 00:27:46.619
What's the remote location?

00:27:46.619 --> 00:27:51.420
And those promises around environment variables

00:27:51.420 --> 00:27:52.900
that will be needed at the time.

00:27:52.900 --> 00:27:55.500
So again, here we have a single command, really,

00:27:55.500 --> 00:27:58.260
at line 10, that sets up your project.

00:27:59.979 --> 00:28:02.140
Then we onboard the data.

00:28:02.140 --> 00:28:07.140
And in this case, we have a very simple dataset

00:28:08.140 --> 00:28:09.380
that we are onboarding.

00:28:09.380 --> 00:28:13.380
But in general, you can onboard any datasets

00:28:13.380 --> 00:28:17.339
bundled together as zip or otherwise into your data product.

00:28:17.339 --> 00:28:18.540
One thing I want to mention here

00:28:18.540 --> 00:28:21.739
is that the notion of data product being versions

00:28:22.619 --> 00:28:24.099
is that it is a snapshot.

00:28:24.099 --> 00:28:25.619
So you may have started live data,

00:28:25.619 --> 00:28:28.540
but you are snapshotting it at that point.

00:28:28.540 --> 00:28:32.219
So there are some datasets that you need to have at hand

00:28:32.219 --> 00:28:34.219
as a snapshot, and then you build your data product.

00:28:34.219 --> 00:28:35.979
So you onboard that data product,

00:28:35.979 --> 00:28:39.060
I'm sorry, your input data into your input folder.

00:28:39.060 --> 00:28:41.300
As I said, there are some environment variables

00:28:41.300 --> 00:28:43.219
that you promised that you will be providing

00:28:43.219 --> 00:28:44.060
at the time of the build.

00:28:44.060 --> 00:28:46.859
So you set those promised environment variables.

00:28:46.859 --> 00:28:48.819
Then there's this step of dpinputmap.

00:28:48.819 --> 00:28:51.180
So you run this command dpinputmap.

00:28:51.219 --> 00:28:54.819
This is a step that we added

00:28:54.819 --> 00:28:58.260
with the mindset of encouraging best practices,

00:28:58.260 --> 00:29:02.540
which in our mind is that if you have some bulk of data,

00:29:02.540 --> 00:29:05.500
it is beneficial to take a look

00:29:05.500 --> 00:29:07.780
before sending everything over.

00:29:07.780 --> 00:29:09.579
In some cases, you know that you want to send

00:29:09.579 --> 00:29:12.020
all of the data that you have put in the input folder over,

00:29:12.020 --> 00:29:12.979
and that's easy.

00:29:12.979 --> 00:29:15.540
In this case of two examples, that's going to be the case.

00:29:15.540 --> 00:29:18.660
But in some cases, you want to look at some metadata.

00:29:18.660 --> 00:29:19.780
Are there duplicate data?

00:29:19.780 --> 00:29:21.819
Are there names that could clash?

00:29:21.819 --> 00:29:24.180
Confusing elements there.

00:29:24.180 --> 00:29:28.699
So there's this step that you do dpinputmap,

00:29:28.699 --> 00:29:30.380
and you get all of that metadata.

00:29:30.380 --> 00:29:31.819
You take a look at it,

00:29:31.819 --> 00:29:33.979
and you pick the elements that you need to sync,

00:29:33.979 --> 00:29:36.699
and you call dpinputsync by setting those flag

00:29:36.699 --> 00:29:38.739
of what data sets you want to sync.

00:29:38.739 --> 00:29:41.060
And this syncing step could take a little while, right?

00:29:41.060 --> 00:29:42.839
Because at this point, literally you're pushing

00:29:42.839 --> 00:29:46.540
the data sets one at a time to your remote location.

00:29:46.540 --> 00:29:48.380
So if you have hundreds of those data sets,

00:29:48.739 --> 00:29:50.780
depending on the size, it could take a little bit.

00:29:50.780 --> 00:29:54.380
And this last step, you're doing dpinputwrite,

00:29:54.380 --> 00:29:56.979
which is actually pretty fast because at this point,

00:29:56.979 --> 00:29:58.819
all of those input data sets that you have synced

00:29:58.819 --> 00:30:00.780
are all metadata code.

00:30:00.780 --> 00:30:02.459
So you're just writing a manifest.

00:30:02.459 --> 00:30:03.500
So it's pretty quick.

00:30:05.140 --> 00:30:08.859
So at this point, let's take a look and see how this looks.

00:30:08.859 --> 00:30:13.619
So we are just writing this cars data set

00:30:13.619 --> 00:30:15.180
into the input folder.

00:30:16.099 --> 00:30:20.939
And so that is the only input data

00:30:20.939 --> 00:30:23.939
that we want to onboard into our data product.

00:30:23.939 --> 00:30:26.459
Next, we are gonna activate the project.

00:30:26.459 --> 00:30:28.020
This assumes that there was a gap

00:30:28.020 --> 00:30:31.300
between this initialization and then this second step.

00:30:31.300 --> 00:30:33.739
If you have already, if you want to go through

00:30:33.739 --> 00:30:35.060
all the way from initialization,

00:30:35.060 --> 00:30:37.219
you don't need to activate again.

00:30:37.219 --> 00:30:40.300
Then you set up those environment variable that we promised.

00:30:40.300 --> 00:30:42.219
So we set up those environment variables,

00:30:42.219 --> 00:30:46.099
and then we capture everything into this config object

00:30:46.099 --> 00:30:49.619
that has metadata, all the elements that we need

00:30:49.619 --> 00:30:53.619
to have at hand for the project to proceed smoothly.

00:30:55.540 --> 00:30:59.380
So now at this point, we only have one data set.

00:30:59.380 --> 00:31:04.219
So we do the input map, and then we essentially know

00:31:04.219 --> 00:31:05.739
that we want to sync this data.

00:31:05.739 --> 00:31:08.140
There's nothing that we want to exclude or change.

00:31:08.140 --> 00:31:10.660
So we just sync by calling dpinputsync.

00:31:10.660 --> 00:31:13.099
Now your input data has been synced.

00:31:13.099 --> 00:31:16.260
This was pretty quick because it was just a simple data,

00:31:16.260 --> 00:31:17.619
a small data set.

00:31:17.619 --> 00:31:19.140
So you get a version for that,

00:31:19.140 --> 00:31:21.540
and now you're doing the right,

00:31:21.540 --> 00:31:23.219
and you're done at this point.

00:31:23.219 --> 00:31:26.339
So now you have converted, you've set up your project,

00:31:26.339 --> 00:31:30.540
you've converted your input into code, onboarded that data,

00:31:30.540 --> 00:31:33.660
and now comes the part that you're gonna be building

00:31:34.939 --> 00:31:37.500
the data product itself, going from input to the output.

00:31:37.500 --> 00:31:39.900
So this is the part that you're gonna be spending your time,

00:31:39.900 --> 00:31:41.900
bringing your subject matter expertise

00:31:41.900 --> 00:31:45.739
to codify all the requirements and all of the user stories

00:31:45.739 --> 00:31:48.500
that you heard about into code

00:31:48.500 --> 00:31:50.900
that does the logic of data wrangling.

00:31:50.900 --> 00:31:52.339
In our case, it's very simple, right?

00:31:52.339 --> 00:31:54.140
You know, we have only changing one column,

00:31:54.140 --> 00:31:57.219
but in essence, it's gonna be exactly the same every time.

00:31:57.219 --> 00:32:00.900
So you have dpinputsread, which reads in all of the input

00:32:00.900 --> 00:32:02.699
data that you have synced and onboarded

00:32:02.699 --> 00:32:04.819
into your data product.

00:32:04.819 --> 00:32:06.979
You add the wrangling logic.

00:32:06.979 --> 00:32:09.819
Then you structure your data object.

00:32:10.619 --> 00:32:11.619
There's this function called dpstructure

00:32:11.619 --> 00:32:13.540
that structures the input, the output,

00:32:13.540 --> 00:32:15.780
metadata all into one object.

00:32:15.780 --> 00:32:18.300
Then similar to dpinputswrite,

00:32:18.300 --> 00:32:21.859
you are registering that data as a metadata now.

00:32:21.859 --> 00:32:24.739
So again, now your input was converted to code.

00:32:24.739 --> 00:32:27.339
Now your output is also converted to code.

00:32:27.339 --> 00:32:31.579
And since everything is code, you do dpcommit and dppush.

00:32:31.579 --> 00:32:36.579
And at this point, you have a repository with README

00:32:37.180 --> 00:32:39.939
and all of the documentation that you need

00:32:39.939 --> 00:32:43.060
to build this data product from scratch.

00:32:43.060 --> 00:32:46.699
Your data product hasn't left your workstation,

00:32:46.699 --> 00:32:48.900
but anybody who has access to the repo

00:32:48.900 --> 00:32:51.699
can build it in their site and push it

00:32:51.699 --> 00:32:53.219
and include it in the CI-CD machine.

00:32:53.219 --> 00:32:55.619
So let's take a look to see how this goes.

00:32:55.619 --> 00:32:57.819
This is gonna be super fast.

00:32:57.819 --> 00:33:00.060
So you read all of the data sets,

00:33:00.060 --> 00:33:03.300
you added your logic, made the output,

00:33:03.300 --> 00:33:05.020
structured it in a data object,

00:33:05.020 --> 00:33:07.260
and then you write it as a YAML file,

00:33:07.260 --> 00:33:10.859
and then you do the dpcommit and dppush,

00:33:10.859 --> 00:33:14.780
and that will generate your repo.

00:33:14.780 --> 00:33:19.780
So at this point, the work is done

00:33:19.780 --> 00:33:23.459
as far as the data developer is concerned,

00:33:23.459 --> 00:33:25.780
and the data can be built.

00:33:25.780 --> 00:33:30.140
But if you wanted to deploy at this point,

00:33:30.140 --> 00:33:32.060
and you don't have to, for example,

00:33:32.060 --> 00:33:35.060
you may be able to commit push a bunch of times

00:33:35.060 --> 00:33:37.020
until you get to a state that your data product

00:33:37.020 --> 00:33:39.060
is at a state that you want to push.

00:33:39.060 --> 00:33:41.099
But let's say you are at that stage

00:33:41.099 --> 00:33:42.619
and you're ready to push,

00:33:42.619 --> 00:33:44.939
so then you call the cpdeploy function,

00:33:44.939 --> 00:33:46.140
it's a single function,

00:33:46.140 --> 00:33:49.260
and it will deploy the data product for you.

00:33:49.260 --> 00:33:50.619
This may take, again, a little bit,

00:33:50.619 --> 00:33:52.540
because at this point, you're also pushing

00:33:52.540 --> 00:33:55.459
your data product to your remote location,

00:33:55.459 --> 00:33:57.300
depending on the size.

00:33:57.300 --> 00:34:00.300
But that essentially concludes the A to Z

00:34:00.300 --> 00:34:01.579
of building the data product.

00:34:01.579 --> 00:34:02.780
Now, if you wanted to access it

00:34:02.780 --> 00:34:05.099
from the persona of a user,

00:34:05.099 --> 00:34:06.900
you only need these three commands,

00:34:06.900 --> 00:34:11.219
dpconnect, which logs into the library

00:34:11.219 --> 00:34:12.580
that has all the data product,

00:34:12.580 --> 00:34:15.860
dplist, it lists all the available data and metadata,

00:34:15.860 --> 00:34:18.860
and dpget, then you can pick from the list

00:34:18.860 --> 00:34:20.419
of data products that you have available.

00:34:20.419 --> 00:34:22.659
So let's take a look at how this works.

00:34:22.659 --> 00:34:25.979
So dpdeploy deploys the data product.

00:34:25.979 --> 00:34:28.260
It doesn't even need any parameters at this point.

00:34:28.260 --> 00:34:30.939
If you have followed the steps as I described,

00:34:32.060 --> 00:34:32.899
this was pretty quick,

00:34:32.899 --> 00:34:34.899
because it was a small data product.

00:34:34.899 --> 00:34:39.219
Then, as a user, now you can access this library

00:34:39.219 --> 00:34:41.060
doing dpconnect.

00:34:42.540 --> 00:34:46.020
And so now you're connected to that library,

00:34:46.020 --> 00:34:47.820
and then you can list the content.

00:34:47.820 --> 00:34:49.739
Now, as the content's being listed,

00:34:49.739 --> 00:34:52.300
perhaps it's worth taking a quick look at it.

00:34:52.300 --> 00:34:53.979
It has a lot of useful metadata,

00:34:53.979 --> 00:34:56.020
like who committed the data,

00:34:56.020 --> 00:34:57.780
what was the commit note,

00:34:57.780 --> 00:34:59.739
what is the git shawl,

00:34:59.739 --> 00:35:01.780
that if I needed to go back to the code,

00:35:02.820 --> 00:35:04.979
how can I pull this specific code,

00:35:04.979 --> 00:35:09.979
and a number of other metadatas that are of use.

00:35:10.459 --> 00:35:13.139
And lastly, if you found your data product

00:35:13.139 --> 00:35:13.979
that you want to pull,

00:35:13.979 --> 00:35:16.100
you can just pull that by version.

00:35:16.100 --> 00:35:19.020
Now, by convention, what we have done

00:35:19.020 --> 00:35:23.020
is that the data product's input contents,

00:35:23.020 --> 00:35:25.300
we keep it as what we call pinlink.

00:35:25.300 --> 00:35:27.060
Essentially, it is a function called

00:35:27.060 --> 00:35:31.020
a specific version of a data that was integrated.

00:35:31.020 --> 00:35:33.820
So the data itself is not integrated

00:35:33.820 --> 00:35:36.739
into the list that is the data object.

00:35:36.739 --> 00:35:39.659
The output, since there are fewer of them,

00:35:39.659 --> 00:35:41.899
we always keep it as a data frame within the data.

00:35:41.899 --> 00:35:44.500
So here you see that I'm pulling an input,

00:35:44.500 --> 00:35:47.100
and it's a function, it's really a function call.

00:35:47.100 --> 00:35:48.860
So I put the input data,

00:35:48.860 --> 00:35:51.379
and then I can pull the output,

00:35:51.379 --> 00:35:55.780
which is an actual data frame connected to the data.

00:35:55.820 --> 00:36:00.820
So we've talked again about this data product

00:36:01.020 --> 00:36:02.260
and what is requirement,

00:36:02.260 --> 00:36:06.139
but how does it feel, how does it look when you look at it?

00:36:06.139 --> 00:36:08.020
The framework doesn't really impose

00:36:08.020 --> 00:36:10.020
any specific structure.

00:36:14.939 --> 00:36:17.939
You can bring in your own structure as you wish,

00:36:17.939 --> 00:36:21.939
but by convention, this is kind of a structure

00:36:21.939 --> 00:36:22.939
that we typically follow.

00:36:22.939 --> 00:36:26.300
So by convention, we always start with data product

00:36:26.300 --> 00:36:29.699
as DT and underscore, perhaps the project name,

00:36:29.699 --> 00:36:31.219
and then some particular topic

00:36:31.219 --> 00:36:34.060
that deals with perhaps a branch of that data product.

00:36:35.939 --> 00:36:38.780
And we have input, output, metadata, README,

00:36:38.780 --> 00:36:40.179
you can have other options.

00:36:41.060 --> 00:36:43.899
So it's comprised of data frames

00:36:43.899 --> 00:36:46.500
and functions that do various things.

00:36:46.500 --> 00:36:48.739
A family of functions that worth to mention

00:36:48.739 --> 00:36:52.020
is this pinlink that I mentioned earlier.

00:36:52.060 --> 00:36:53.699
So let's say you have this data product,

00:36:53.699 --> 00:36:54.939
it's had some input,

00:36:54.939 --> 00:36:56.459
you look at the clinical component

00:36:56.459 --> 00:36:58.459
that you're interested in the demographics.

00:36:58.459 --> 00:37:00.379
At this point, at this leaf,

00:37:00.379 --> 00:37:01.780
you have in the list,

00:37:01.780 --> 00:37:03.260
you really have a function called

00:37:03.260 --> 00:37:07.659
to a specific version of this demographic data.

00:37:07.659 --> 00:37:09.820
So it's not part of your data,

00:37:09.820 --> 00:37:12.340
but you can pull it in as needed.

00:37:12.340 --> 00:37:14.459
So what happens is typically we have

00:37:14.459 --> 00:37:17.379
hundreds of these input data sets,

00:37:17.379 --> 00:37:20.820
and either all of them are fairly decent size,

00:37:20.820 --> 00:37:22.100
but the data product itself,

00:37:22.100 --> 00:37:23.219
the size of it is pretty small

00:37:23.219 --> 00:37:25.300
because all of these are actual function calls,

00:37:25.300 --> 00:37:27.219
they are not data.

00:37:27.219 --> 00:37:30.419
But convention, since we have fewer of these outputs,

00:37:30.419 --> 00:37:31.659
we keep them as data frames.

00:37:31.659 --> 00:37:33.219
So you have data for analysis A,

00:37:33.219 --> 00:37:34.699
data for analysis B,

00:37:34.699 --> 00:37:37.100
you have some metadata and README and such.

00:37:37.979 --> 00:37:41.219
The output can absolutely also be pinlinks if needed,

00:37:41.219 --> 00:37:44.939
but the need hasn't been there so far.

00:37:44.939 --> 00:37:46.820
So as you're thinking about this,

00:37:46.820 --> 00:37:49.419
some limitations and constraints,

00:37:49.419 --> 00:37:52.300
Dapr deals with tabular data,

00:37:52.300 --> 00:37:53.979
but does not natively impose

00:37:53.979 --> 00:37:55.899
or accommodate relational data models.

00:37:55.899 --> 00:37:58.100
So that is consideration.

00:37:58.100 --> 00:38:00.979
Dapr is not intended for large data tables.

00:38:00.979 --> 00:38:05.979
So if you have a bunch of smallish to medium sized tables,

00:38:07.540 --> 00:38:08.540
hundreds of megabytes,

00:38:08.540 --> 00:38:10.820
you have hundreds of them, totally fine.

00:38:10.820 --> 00:38:14.300
If you have single data tables that are gigantic,

00:38:15.979 --> 00:38:18.620
at this point, we have some ideas how to deal with it,

00:38:18.620 --> 00:38:20.659
but it hasn't been part of the use cases

00:38:20.659 --> 00:38:24.500
that we have worked on and it's not supported.

00:38:25.699 --> 00:38:27.540
So Dapr does not address data governance.

00:38:27.540 --> 00:38:29.659
I would be glad to talk a little bit more about that.

00:38:29.659 --> 00:38:32.340
But instead of actually looking at this as a shortcoming,

00:38:32.340 --> 00:38:35.379
I look at this as an opportunity for collaboration

00:38:36.540 --> 00:38:38.340
across the team.

00:38:38.340 --> 00:38:40.979
So you can work with the data platforms

00:38:40.979 --> 00:38:42.620
that have a lot of knobs and levers

00:38:42.620 --> 00:38:46.260
that allow granular access being managed.

00:38:46.260 --> 00:38:50.219
But that is not part of the elements

00:38:50.219 --> 00:38:52.379
that is managed by Dapr.

00:38:52.379 --> 00:38:53.780
And most importantly,

00:38:53.780 --> 00:38:56.939
Dapr and packages that it is built upon are very young.

00:38:56.939 --> 00:38:59.860
So Dapr itself is not that old,

00:38:59.860 --> 00:39:01.820
and pins and RN,

00:39:01.820 --> 00:39:03.540
which are integral to its functionality,

00:39:03.540 --> 00:39:04.620
are also quite young.

00:39:05.979 --> 00:39:08.659
So in summary, I'm hoping at this point,

00:39:08.659 --> 00:39:10.939
some of you see some value

00:39:10.939 --> 00:39:13.540
and agree that with a minimal amount of work,

00:39:13.540 --> 00:39:15.219
which we showed in those videos,

00:39:16.179 --> 00:39:18.020
it doesn't take a whole lot of time,

00:39:18.020 --> 00:39:20.659
you can take your current data wrangling

00:39:20.659 --> 00:39:24.820
and trade it up to get a data product

00:39:24.820 --> 00:39:27.659
that comes with all of those attributes

00:39:27.659 --> 00:39:31.340
and guarantees that hopefully make the experience

00:39:31.340 --> 00:39:33.020
of the user much more pleasant

00:39:33.020 --> 00:39:38.020
and build efficiency as well across the team.

00:39:39.419 --> 00:39:41.100
This is very much a project

00:39:41.100 --> 00:39:42.939
that we are both heavily using

00:39:42.939 --> 00:39:44.899
as a consumer of this framework,

00:39:45.580 --> 00:39:46.620
but also we are developing.

00:39:46.620 --> 00:39:48.620
And a lot of the development falls

00:39:48.620 --> 00:39:51.620
along the cycle of DevOps,

00:39:51.620 --> 00:39:54.419
but here we are having it for data.

00:39:54.419 --> 00:39:57.139
To just mention some of these examples of projects

00:39:57.139 --> 00:39:57.979
that we are working on.

00:39:57.979 --> 00:40:02.699
So we are working on an information-based diffing of data.

00:40:02.699 --> 00:40:07.699
This is a work that we had a great colleague

00:40:08.540 --> 00:40:09.939
joining us for the summer

00:40:10.780 --> 00:40:15.699
and contributed to building this DDiff package.

00:40:15.699 --> 00:40:20.699
And we also are building vignettes

00:40:21.219 --> 00:40:23.219
around how to automate.

00:40:23.219 --> 00:40:27.379
So CICD, you know, set up data testing

00:40:27.379 --> 00:40:28.739
is another element that we want

00:40:28.739 --> 00:40:29.939
to kind of build vignettes around

00:40:29.939 --> 00:40:32.260
so how folks can integrate data testing

00:40:32.260 --> 00:40:36.179
into the workflow and some work

00:40:36.179 --> 00:40:37.459
around adding additional metadata

00:40:37.459 --> 00:40:38.780
to enable observability.

00:40:38.780 --> 00:40:41.659
And lastly, something that is interesting

00:40:41.659 --> 00:40:43.780
is that since data is recipe,

00:40:43.780 --> 00:40:45.379
you can spin it up and spin it down.

00:40:45.379 --> 00:40:49.060
So demand-based deployment could be something

00:40:49.060 --> 00:40:54.060
that could help save storage if that is ever a concern.

00:40:54.379 --> 00:40:57.820
So with that, I just wanted to take a moment again

00:40:57.820 --> 00:41:02.739
to thank our CIFARMA meetup organizers and community.

00:41:02.739 --> 00:41:05.260
And I need to acknowledge the efforts

00:41:05.260 --> 00:41:08.419
of a lot of colleagues who have contributed,

00:41:09.060 --> 00:41:11.139
thoughts, ideas, support one way or another

00:41:11.139 --> 00:41:12.340
to this project.

00:41:12.340 --> 00:41:16.020
And last but not least, all of you for tuning in today.

00:41:16.020 --> 00:41:18.820
Yeah, I'd love to kind of talk a little bit more

00:41:18.820 --> 00:41:20.219
and address some questions.

00:41:23.580 --> 00:41:25.860
Awesome, thank you so much, Afshin.

00:41:25.860 --> 00:41:27.659
And let me bring Phil over here too.

00:41:29.179 --> 00:41:32.419
Awesome, I see, great, that was a great presentation.

00:41:32.419 --> 00:41:33.580
Thank you so much.

00:41:33.580 --> 00:41:37.580
There are a lot of questions starting to come in on Slido.

00:41:37.620 --> 00:41:39.540
So I just wanna remind everybody

00:41:39.540 --> 00:41:41.659
that you can ask questions wherever you are.

00:41:41.659 --> 00:41:45.139
So if you're watching on LinkedIn, you can ask there

00:41:45.139 --> 00:41:46.139
and we'll see them.

