Yeah, so I'll try to,

00:46:36.780 --> 00:46:39.699
and please chime in if I'm not addressing your question.

00:46:39.699 --> 00:46:44.699
So we do, so the code itself,

00:46:45.260 --> 00:46:47.540
the package itself generates code.

00:46:48.620 --> 00:46:53.620
So it does provide some template code

00:46:53.939 --> 00:46:55.219
when I talked about Blueprint.

00:46:55.219 --> 00:46:56.860
So when you're starting your project,

00:46:56.860 --> 00:47:00.699
it populates your folder with some base wiring

00:47:00.699 --> 00:47:03.100
that then you can add to.

00:47:03.100 --> 00:47:04.620
I don't know if that's what you refer to

00:47:04.620 --> 00:47:07.540
as the vanilla code or not, or maybe I'm,

00:47:07.540 --> 00:47:10.379
but if that's the idea is that,

00:47:10.379 --> 00:47:12.580
yeah, so as you're starting your project,

00:47:13.979 --> 00:47:17.580
it does add some starter code

00:47:17.580 --> 00:47:20.820
for you to be able to wire your project together.

00:47:20.820 --> 00:47:24.379
But I have a feeling that doesn't address the question.

00:47:24.379 --> 00:47:27.060
Yeah, and we can clarify on LinkedIn too,

00:47:27.060 --> 00:47:29.340
if that was your question, or on YouTube.

00:47:29.340 --> 00:47:31.780
People can ask questions there too.

00:47:31.780 --> 00:47:35.179
I see there was another question on Slido,

00:47:37.139 --> 00:47:40.580
which is, how has it been implementing

00:47:40.580 --> 00:47:45.179
the data as a product framework for a multilingual team?

00:47:45.179 --> 00:47:47.500
Does your environment support Python and R,

00:47:48.379 --> 00:47:50.379
and do you use Connect for this?

00:47:50.379 --> 00:47:53.100
Yeah, I really love this question,

00:47:53.100 --> 00:47:57.020
and because it is one of the things

00:47:57.020 --> 00:48:00.300
that definitely on my mind,

00:48:00.300 --> 00:48:03.179
at this point, it is primarily R, right?

00:48:06.139 --> 00:48:08.620
Pins, which is an awesome package,

00:48:08.620 --> 00:48:12.659
so shout out to the RStudio developers for Pins,

00:48:12.659 --> 00:48:15.939
is at the core of this dapper.

00:48:15.939 --> 00:48:20.939
Pins is a package that supports both Python and R,

00:48:23.620 --> 00:48:27.659
and so the data products being Pins

00:48:27.659 --> 00:48:31.939
can be pulled in theory by Python as well as R.

00:48:31.939 --> 00:48:33.699
Now, when it comes to the development,

00:48:33.699 --> 00:48:35.620
like we are talking about an end-to-end,

00:48:35.620 --> 00:48:38.419
so we can get a recipe and can build it up.

00:48:38.419 --> 00:48:40.219
Of course, that code is written in R.

00:48:40.219 --> 00:48:41.699
Of course, the packages are written in R.

00:48:41.699 --> 00:48:45.459
So in theory, it is totally feasible

00:48:45.459 --> 00:48:50.459
to write R code in a way that interfaces with Python

00:48:50.939 --> 00:48:53.939
and or vice versa,

00:48:53.939 --> 00:48:58.939
and have a sister package that essentially manages that

00:48:59.060 --> 00:49:01.219
where the code itself, if you wanted to reproduce it,

00:49:01.219 --> 00:49:02.820
not if you wanted to use it, as I said,

00:49:02.820 --> 00:49:04.979
if you want to just use it,

00:49:04.979 --> 00:49:07.899
you can absolutely use the Pins,

00:49:07.899 --> 00:49:10.899
which is at the core of this by Python or R,

00:49:10.899 --> 00:49:12.540
but if you're developing it,

00:49:12.540 --> 00:49:14.939
there is some dependency on the environments

00:49:14.939 --> 00:49:15.899
that you're developing on.

00:49:15.899 --> 00:49:18.939
So it can be done in theory,

00:49:18.939 --> 00:49:21.699
but perhaps it's better to kind of choose

00:49:21.699 --> 00:49:22.540
where you want to be.

00:49:22.540 --> 00:49:24.459
And in terms of going back and forth,

00:49:24.459 --> 00:49:25.979
again, I think it's feasible.

00:49:25.979 --> 00:49:29.179
It's just a matter of that development taking place.

00:49:29.179 --> 00:49:32.899
At this point, that hasn't been done.

00:49:34.260 --> 00:49:35.219
A great question.

00:49:37.739 --> 00:49:40.139
Thank you, and I am just scrolling over

00:49:40.139 --> 00:49:42.699
to see if there are other questions,

00:49:42.699 --> 00:49:44.780
and I'm not seeing them pop up yet,

00:49:45.620 --> 00:49:46.459
but I just want to turn it over to you, Phil,

00:49:46.459 --> 00:49:49.419
to see if you have a general question you want to ask too.

00:49:51.060 --> 00:49:53.580
So many thoughts around this.

00:49:54.580 --> 00:49:57.260
What's it like with new users coming into this?

00:49:57.260 --> 00:49:58.860
Is there a certain type of training?

00:49:58.860 --> 00:50:03.179
Is data as a product and data wrangling and CICD?

00:50:03.179 --> 00:50:06.739
I would say are newer methodologies coming in.

00:50:06.739 --> 00:50:08.860
What's it like for people coming to this new

00:50:08.860 --> 00:50:11.780
or used to running these things more manually

00:50:11.780 --> 00:50:13.860
or in like a batch mode?

00:50:13.899 --> 00:50:14.739
Absolutely.

00:50:14.739 --> 00:50:17.060
So again, I want to kind of distinguish

00:50:17.060 --> 00:50:18.939
between folks coming to this as a user

00:50:18.939 --> 00:50:20.179
or folks coming to this as a developer.

00:50:20.179 --> 00:50:23.739
So as a user, I think it's pretty straightforward.

00:50:23.739 --> 00:50:26.379
So the kind of ramp up to like,

00:50:26.379 --> 00:50:28.939
okay, this is the data library and I can pull in.

00:50:28.939 --> 00:50:30.340
So that part is much easier.

00:50:30.340 --> 00:50:31.620
And then as a developer,

00:50:31.620 --> 00:50:33.820
of course, there's more involved here, right?

00:50:34.780 --> 00:50:38.459
And I want to kind of say that how critical this is,

00:50:38.459 --> 00:50:40.340
and this is one of the things that we have learned

00:50:40.340 --> 00:50:44.219
since the first time we presented on this.

00:50:44.219 --> 00:50:45.659
Technology goes so far.

00:50:45.659 --> 00:50:47.219
It is really about these,

00:50:47.219 --> 00:50:49.260
when it comes to these DevOps practices,

00:50:49.260 --> 00:50:50.580
it's really about culture.

00:50:50.580 --> 00:50:52.260
It's really about the collaboration.

00:50:52.260 --> 00:50:56.899
So it's been absolutely critical for us

00:50:56.899 --> 00:51:01.899
to be able to forge those relations and commitments

00:51:02.020 --> 00:51:05.899
and change in the mindset of how we are doing data.

00:51:05.899 --> 00:51:07.979
So it is a commitment.

00:51:07.979 --> 00:51:09.580
It is something that folks need to say,

00:51:09.580 --> 00:51:13.459
okay, I'm going to commit to being able to,

00:51:13.459 --> 00:51:15.580
or kind of like incurring this cost,

00:51:15.580 --> 00:51:19.459
establishing my data infrastructure in this way.

00:51:20.860 --> 00:51:25.100
And that commitment leads to some changes in how,

00:51:25.100 --> 00:51:28.020
like the question of when the data is done.

00:51:28.020 --> 00:51:30.739
It is a parallel to question to when we are done

00:51:30.739 --> 00:51:32.939
and analyzing TCGA, for example.

00:51:32.939 --> 00:51:34.020
No one asked that question

00:51:34.020 --> 00:51:35.620
because there's so many questions

00:51:35.620 --> 00:51:37.500
you can ask from that data set.

00:51:37.540 --> 00:51:41.899
So building that mental bridge and cultural shift,

00:51:41.899 --> 00:51:45.219
I think is something that takes time.

00:51:45.219 --> 00:51:46.620
From the technology perspective,

00:51:46.620 --> 00:51:48.540
learning the code and all of that,

00:51:48.540 --> 00:51:52.459
I feel someone going through it a couple of times,

00:51:52.459 --> 00:51:54.899
they will be able to pick it up.

00:51:54.899 --> 00:51:57.300
And one learning again that we have had

00:51:57.300 --> 00:52:00.139
is that it is really important for those in the team

00:52:00.139 --> 00:52:02.020
who are a little bit more experienced

00:52:02.020 --> 00:52:07.020
to lower the kind of the entry barriers a little bit.

00:52:07.219 --> 00:52:09.139
So you bring in your wrangling code,

00:52:09.139 --> 00:52:10.260
you can work with your colleagues

00:52:10.260 --> 00:52:12.300
to integrate that into Dapr.

00:52:12.300 --> 00:52:14.979
And then from that point on, they can maintain it.

00:52:14.979 --> 00:52:17.179
So it's a little bit of a commitment,

00:52:17.179 --> 00:52:21.020
but it's something that once folks make that commitment,

00:52:21.020 --> 00:52:24.739
I think within a course of a month or so,

00:52:24.739 --> 00:52:27.899
they can fully be in this cycle

00:52:27.899 --> 00:52:30.659
of developing the data across the team.

00:52:32.179 --> 00:52:33.820
And for surfacing out the data

00:52:33.820 --> 00:52:36.100
and for people looking for and finding,

00:52:36.100 --> 00:52:38.899
is there like a data dictionary or a system

00:52:38.899 --> 00:52:40.540
or do they go into an environment?

00:52:40.540 --> 00:52:41.379
Because someone says,

00:52:41.379 --> 00:52:44.780
I want this assay data or this research data.

00:52:44.780 --> 00:52:47.179
How do they go about locating that?

00:52:47.179 --> 00:52:48.340
Yeah, absolutely.

00:52:48.340 --> 00:52:52.860
So building additional metadata

00:52:52.860 --> 00:52:54.500
that makes the dataset searchable

00:52:54.500 --> 00:52:58.860
is certainly something that there's room for

00:52:58.860 --> 00:53:00.100
to build additional metadata.

00:53:00.100 --> 00:53:05.100
At this point, the owner of the data,

00:53:06.219 --> 00:53:08.300
folks who are subject matter experts

00:53:09.139 --> 00:53:12.939
are perhaps the best people to connect with.

00:53:12.939 --> 00:53:15.860
So if you, I'm saying it is absolutely possible

00:53:15.860 --> 00:53:16.820
to put metadata out there,

00:53:16.820 --> 00:53:20.500
but the preferred route is a lot of times

00:53:20.500 --> 00:53:23.419
folks want to just kind of go fishing for data, right?

00:53:23.419 --> 00:53:25.219
And a lot of the context may be missed.

00:53:25.219 --> 00:53:27.979
So if they have specific questions

00:53:27.979 --> 00:53:29.820
that you know you work within a team

00:53:29.820 --> 00:53:33.540
and you know like this team actually owns a data product.

00:53:33.540 --> 00:53:36.659
So it's just a matter of having that conversation up front

00:53:36.659 --> 00:53:38.139
and then that kind of eithers it in.

00:53:38.139 --> 00:53:42.580
So in a way they kind of like a global world of metadata

00:53:42.580 --> 00:53:44.939
allow folks to kind of like drill down

00:53:44.939 --> 00:53:46.939
and get exactly what they want.

00:53:46.939 --> 00:53:49.139
It has been prioritized with respect

00:53:49.139 --> 00:53:52.340
to like more personal connections on these data products,

00:53:52.340 --> 00:53:54.820
but absolutely doable to add metadata.

00:53:54.820 --> 00:53:58.739
And do traditional data environments like databases

00:53:58.739 --> 00:54:02.419
and maybe even larger distributed data sources,

00:54:02.419 --> 00:54:03.860
does that also play into here

00:54:03.860 --> 00:54:07.540
or is this more for flat files or?

00:54:07.540 --> 00:54:08.379
No, absolutely.

00:54:08.379 --> 00:54:13.379
So we, a data product in examples that we have worked on

00:54:14.899 --> 00:54:17.580
brings in data from a diversity of sources.

00:54:17.580 --> 00:54:21.540
So you may have a traditional relational database

00:54:21.540 --> 00:54:22.659
that there's a table you want.

00:54:22.659 --> 00:54:24.459
So you bring that in

00:54:24.459 --> 00:54:26.340
and then you augment it with a table

00:54:26.340 --> 00:54:29.620
that you have curated yourself of medications

00:54:29.620 --> 00:54:32.300
and the classifications, for example.

00:54:33.179 --> 00:54:38.179
The key element is that unlike some of these relational,

00:54:39.060 --> 00:54:41.620
unlike some of these data repositories

00:54:41.620 --> 00:54:44.739
or data platforms that are live data

00:54:44.739 --> 00:54:46.419
that could change anytime,

00:54:46.419 --> 00:54:47.540
here we are to snapshotting.

00:54:47.540 --> 00:54:49.300
So every time you're bringing it,

00:54:49.300 --> 00:54:51.659
you're taking a snapshot of that state

00:54:51.659 --> 00:54:54.020
and then you onboard it into your data product.

00:54:54.020 --> 00:54:55.699
And do you have scheduling components?

00:54:55.699 --> 00:54:58.100
Like if they say, hey, pull this every day at 9 a.m.,

00:54:58.100 --> 00:55:01.340
run this and then when the scientists wanna access the data

00:55:01.340 --> 00:55:04.620
it's routinely updated with the new lab data, for example.

00:55:04.620 --> 00:55:07.300
Yeah, so that can absolutely be done.

00:55:08.219 --> 00:55:12.540
We haven't had the kind of automation of that as a use case.

00:55:12.540 --> 00:55:14.699
