00:58:28.580 --> 00:58:30.659
So right now, so the idea is,

00:58:30.659 --> 00:58:33.379
if you're thinking about your data and codes

00:58:33.379 --> 00:58:35.020
to be kind of interchangeable,

00:58:35.020 --> 00:58:37.739
when you're writing a code and you committed

00:58:37.739 --> 00:58:38.580
and then someone says, okay,

00:58:38.580 --> 00:58:40.219
what's the difference between this version

00:58:40.219 --> 00:58:41.820
and the previous version?

00:58:41.820 --> 00:58:44.179
You do a DDIF and get this,

00:58:44.179 --> 00:58:46.659
and it will tell you like the lines of code that has changed.

00:58:46.659 --> 00:58:49.739
Now, imagine you have two columns of data.

00:58:49.739 --> 00:58:52.100
Everything is multiplied by two.

00:58:52.860 --> 00:58:54.899
Now, every single element in the million rows

00:58:54.899 --> 00:58:57.020
is going to pop up as text different, right?

00:58:57.020 --> 00:58:59.580
You know, you started with one, one becomes two.

00:58:59.580 --> 00:59:01.780
But from an information perspective,

00:59:01.780 --> 00:59:03.060
nothing much has changed.

00:59:03.060 --> 00:59:05.179
You know, you have just multiplied everything by a factor.

00:59:05.179 --> 00:59:09.260
So when we would like to be able to do the DDIF

00:59:09.260 --> 00:59:12.899
on the data side, that is as actionable

00:59:12.899 --> 00:59:15.100
as when you do a DDIF on the text side.

00:59:15.100 --> 00:59:17.100
And if you want to use the text-based DDIF,

00:59:17.100 --> 00:59:18.899
which are a lot of good packages out there

00:59:18.899 --> 00:59:21.340
that does that in R4U,

00:59:21.340 --> 00:59:22.939
you don't get that information base.

00:59:22.939 --> 00:59:26.139
You don't see how the likelihood of the data now has shifted.

00:59:26.139 --> 00:59:28.540
So if you were to say, if you come up with a score

00:59:28.540 --> 00:59:33.100
that says, oh, your data shifted by, you know, 0.02,

00:59:33.100 --> 00:59:35.899
you know, I know that's kind of perhaps a high bar,

00:59:35.899 --> 00:59:37.659
but that is an actionable thing.

00:59:37.659 --> 00:59:40.139
It's like, I don't need to run my ML model

00:59:40.139 --> 00:59:41.739
