01:08:25.020 --> 01:08:29.180
in terms of folks being able to have ability

01:08:29.180 --> 01:08:32.060
to go across and check the work, so.

01:08:32.060 --> 01:08:33.220
Yeah, yeah.

01:08:33.220 --> 01:08:35.220
Do you see Shiny being a part of that

01:08:35.220 --> 01:08:37.020
and consuming some of these data products

01:08:37.020 --> 01:08:38.379
or surfacing them out?

01:08:39.339 --> 01:08:40.180
Absolutely.

01:08:40.180 --> 01:08:43.299
I mean, I think when you zoom out,

01:08:43.299 --> 01:08:47.899
you see this Vista that you have data and inference

01:08:47.899 --> 01:08:50.939
and then Shiny is like a user interface for all of it.

01:08:50.939 --> 01:08:54.979
So one thing that is very, very relevant to Shiny

01:08:54.979 --> 01:08:57.140
and I would say RStudio Connect,

01:08:57.140 --> 01:09:01.500
we are heavily using that because what happens

01:09:01.500 --> 01:09:04.819
is this data product I shared at the end of the day,

01:09:04.819 --> 01:09:07.620
it's a programmatic accessible object.

01:09:07.620 --> 01:09:09.859
It needs to have, if you want to collaborate

01:09:10.540 --> 01:09:11.899
with that, you know, colleague of yours

01:09:11.899 --> 01:09:15.259
who has tremendous amount of information on the biology

01:09:15.259 --> 01:09:16.819
or on the clinical side,

01:09:16.819 --> 01:09:18.379
they want to be able to interface that

01:09:18.379 --> 01:09:19.939
through a user interface.

01:09:19.939 --> 01:09:22.060
So we build these automated reports

01:09:22.060 --> 01:09:26.220
that brings in the data products and surfaces them.

01:09:26.220 --> 01:09:29.299
So, you know, the MDs and, you know,

01:09:29.299 --> 01:09:33.459
the biologists can really dig deep

01:09:33.459 --> 01:09:36.620
and then feedback, so go ahead and change your data.

01:09:36.620 --> 01:09:38.700
So then this becomes part of that DevOps cycle.

01:09:38.700 --> 01:09:40.660
So the data itself iterates

01:09:40.660 --> 01:09:42.899
and we are getting all of that feedback

01:09:42.899 --> 01:09:45.700
through Shiny, through the R Markdowns

01:09:45.700 --> 01:09:47.819
and the interface between the two of them.

01:09:50.299 --> 01:09:52.979
If it's okay, so what was it like going from,

01:09:52.979 --> 01:09:55.580
you know, statistics, statistician type work

01:09:55.580 --> 01:09:58.379
to so much data wrangling, data engineering,

01:09:58.379 --> 01:10:01.180
data, I mean, it's such a awesome area

01:10:01.180 --> 01:10:02.339
that you're working in now.

01:10:02.339 --> 01:10:04.540
What was that transition like for you?

01:10:04.540 --> 01:10:05.459
Yeah, no, absolutely.

01:10:05.459 --> 01:10:07.459
I mean, what really inspired,

01:10:07.459 --> 01:10:09.259
so I started my career as an engineer,

01:10:09.259 --> 01:10:12.580
no data, I was building hard work.

01:10:12.580 --> 01:10:14.379
And then I saw data, I was like,

01:10:14.379 --> 01:10:15.220
I gotta get my hands on that.

01:10:15.220 --> 01:10:20.100
So I went and got training in biostatistics.

01:10:20.100 --> 01:10:20.939
Yeah.

01:10:20.939 --> 01:10:24.299
And then once I was working developing algorithms,

01:10:24.299 --> 01:10:28.779
I started building, so I was developing algorithms

01:10:28.779 --> 01:10:32.620
for, you know, kind of data mining

01:10:32.620 --> 01:10:34.339
on publicly available data

01:10:34.339 --> 01:10:36.540
and building, you know, genetic signature.

01:10:36.580 --> 01:10:39.899
I realized that what really matters,

01:10:39.899 --> 01:10:41.500
and this is something that we are hearing

01:10:41.500 --> 01:10:43.859
in the concept of data centric AI,

01:10:43.859 --> 01:10:45.979
particularly in biomedical research.

01:10:45.979 --> 01:10:46.819
This is good.

01:10:46.819 --> 01:10:48.500
If you were to spend a dollar,

01:10:48.500 --> 01:10:51.620
if you spent 70 cents of that dollar on data

01:10:51.620 --> 01:10:53.859
and 30 cents of that on, you know,

01:10:53.859 --> 01:10:56.700
your new fancy algorithms that is coming,

01:10:56.700 --> 01:10:58.620
you would be much better off

01:10:58.620 --> 01:11:00.580
than doing it the other way around.

01:11:00.580 --> 01:11:01.419
Yeah.

01:11:01.419 --> 01:11:04.939
There's a lot of value to be, you know,

01:11:04.939 --> 01:11:06.419
kind of retrieved from the data work.

01:11:07.259 --> 01:11:10.660
So that is really what drew me more and more into this.

01:11:10.660 --> 01:11:13.259
And I think that is bio,

01:11:13.259 --> 01:11:16.540
like if you think about a row of data in biological data,

01:11:17.700 --> 01:11:20.620
compared that to click data that is maybe in the industry

01:11:20.620 --> 01:11:21.979
of, you know, when you think about, you know,

01:11:21.979 --> 01:11:24.620
other industries outside bio,

01:11:24.620 --> 01:11:26.899
that row of data could worth, you know,

01:11:26.899 --> 01:11:29.020
hundreds of thousands of dollars.

01:11:29.020 --> 01:11:29.859
Yeah.

01:11:29.859 --> 01:11:31.660
So in terms of actual,

01:11:31.660 --> 01:11:33.580
and if you can put a dollar value on it,

01:11:33.580 --> 01:11:35.339
it's super precious.

01:11:35.339 --> 01:11:36.180
Yeah.

01:11:36.180 --> 01:11:40.140
So efforts on the data for me was an awakening.

01:11:40.140 --> 01:11:43.540
Like I am doing this statistic machine learning

01:11:43.540 --> 01:11:45.140
algorithm development.

01:11:45.140 --> 01:11:45.979
Yeah.

01:11:45.979 --> 01:11:50.100
But if I can shift my focus a little bit towards the data,

01:11:50.100 --> 01:11:55.100
you know, there's a lot of ripe opportunities.

01:11:55.580 --> 01:11:58.259
There's so much excitement in the space right now.

01:11:58.259 --> 01:12:01.060
You were mentioning algorithms around, you know,

01:12:01.060 --> 01:12:03.419
deep learning, AI first principles,

01:12:03.419 --> 01:12:06.100
impacting, especially drug discovery.

01:12:06.100 --> 01:12:08.379
Are you seeing and being part of that too,

01:12:08.379 --> 01:12:09.779
as well right now?

01:12:09.779 --> 01:12:10.620
No, absolutely.

01:12:10.620 --> 01:12:14.060
I mean, there's tremendous amount of excitement

01:12:14.060 --> 01:12:15.620
about AI in all industries.

01:12:15.620 --> 01:12:18.060
And, you know, pharma is no exception,

01:12:18.060 --> 01:12:20.939
particularly when it comes to, you know,

01:12:20.939 --> 01:12:24.060
new therapeutics being developed using AI and all of that.

01:12:24.060 --> 01:12:27.220
I personally am not part of that effort,

01:12:27.220 --> 01:12:28.620
but what I've seen, you know,

01:12:28.620 --> 01:12:31.339
as someone who has come from that background

01:12:31.339 --> 01:12:33.140
of a statistics machine learning,

01:12:33.140 --> 01:12:38.140
is that there is a lot of excitement on that AI front,

01:12:38.459 --> 01:12:43.220
rightly so, but I would say there is room

01:12:43.220 --> 01:12:46.299
to get a lot more excited about the data itself.

01:12:46.299 --> 01:12:51.299
So I think Android has this really cool, you know,

01:12:52.020 --> 01:12:56.779
set of ideas about, you can iterate on your model

01:12:56.779 --> 01:13:00.580
a bunch of times and you go, you know, this far,

01:13:00.580 --> 01:13:03.540
you can iterate on your data and you go this far.

01:13:03.540 --> 01:13:06.979
So that is something that I feel particularly in biofield

01:13:06.979 --> 01:13:08.779
needs a little bit more effort.

01:13:08.779 --> 01:13:11.580
And all of those cool algorithms that you use

01:13:11.580 --> 01:13:16.140
on the learning side can actually be applied

01:13:16.140 --> 01:13:17.459
to the data side.

01:13:18.459 --> 01:13:22.100
A lot of unsupervised learning algorithms

01:13:22.100 --> 01:13:24.220
have tremendous value on the data side.

01:13:24.220 --> 01:13:28.180
So I see an opportunity more and more

01:13:28.580 --> 01:13:31.180
for focusing on that area.

01:13:31.180 --> 01:13:34.899
The data is the common thread throughout all of that.

01:13:34.899 --> 01:13:37.779
Do you also get involved on the massive data side,

01:13:37.779 --> 01:13:42.779
like the large data sources, Spark, HDFS, things like that?

01:13:43.060 --> 01:13:46.060
Does that come up much with the data engineering side of it?

01:13:47.540 --> 01:13:51.299
Well, we do have massive data that comes along

01:13:51.299 --> 01:13:56.299
and in the context that I have been involved

01:13:56.459 --> 01:13:58.660
for machine learning purposes,

01:13:59.740 --> 01:14:04.740
a lot of the data in pharma, we are not very long data.

01:14:05.259 --> 01:14:06.500
We are wide data.

01:14:08.459 --> 01:14:11.020
A trial could have a hundred folks, a hundred people in it,

01:14:11.020 --> 01:14:13.020
could be hundreds of millions of dollars.

01:14:13.020 --> 01:14:15.419
So you have for that one patient, you know,

01:14:15.419 --> 01:14:18.660
millions of attributes that you're collecting.

01:14:18.660 --> 01:14:20.859
So a lot of the, I think a lot of the machine learning,

01:14:20.859 --> 01:14:24.819
a lot of the algorithms typically have been in the realm

01:14:24.819 --> 01:14:28.660
of being able to address high dimensional data.

01:14:30.459 --> 01:14:31.779
And, you know, in the industry

01:14:31.779 --> 01:14:33.299
where you have very long data,

01:14:33.299 --> 01:14:35.339
you know, folks using Spark and others,

01:14:35.339 --> 01:14:38.259
there's absolutely, it hasn't been in my experience.

01:14:38.259 --> 01:14:41.100
So I'm sure it's in like other, you know,

01:14:41.100 --> 01:14:43.660
colleagues within my company are leveraging that.

01:14:43.660 --> 01:14:45.419
But in the world that I am part of,

01:14:46.779 --> 01:14:49.419
our big data has been the wide data.

01:14:49.419 --> 01:14:51.620
Yeah, yeah, lots of stuff.

